---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import RothConversionCalculator from "../../components/RothConversionCalculator.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Roth Conversion Calculator | Traditional IRA to Roth Tax Impact"
  description="Model the tax cost of converting a traditional IRA or 401(k) to a Roth IRA, and see the breakeven retirement tax rate where conversion pays off."
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" slot="head">
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@graph": [
      {
        "@type": "FinanceApplication",
        "name": "Roth Conversion Calculator",
        "applicationCategory": "FinanceApplication",
        "operatingSystem": "Web",
        "provider": {
          "@id": "https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/#organization"
        },
        "offers": {
          "@type": "Offer",
          "price": "0",
          "priceCurrency": "USD"
        },
        "description": "Model the tax cost of converting a traditional IRA or 401(k) to a Roth IRA, and see the breakeven retirement tax rate where conversion pays off."
      },
      {
        "@type": "FAQPage",
        "mainEntity": [
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Why would I pay taxes now instead of later?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "Converting makes the most sense when your current marginal tax rate is lower than the rate you expect to pay in retirement — for example, in a low-income year, after a business loss, or before required minimum distributions push you into a higher bracket later."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What's the difference between paying conversion tax from the IRA vs. from savings?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "Paying the conversion tax from outside savings lets the full converted amount grow tax-free in the Roth. Paying it from the IRA itself reduces the amount that converts and grows tax-free, and for those under 59½ it may also count as an early withdrawal subject to a 10% penalty on that portion."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Can I convert only part of my traditional IRA?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "Yes. Many people convert smaller amounts over several years — sometimes called a conversion ladder — to stay within a target tax bracket each year rather than converting a large balance all at once."
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
        "itemListElement": [
          {
            "@type": "ListItem",
            "position": 1,
            "name": "Home",
            "item": "https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/"
          },
          {
            "@type": "ListItem",
            "position": 2,
            "name": "Roth Conversion Calculator",
            "item": "https://taxdebtwealthsuite.com/roth-conversion-calculator/"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
  </script>

  <main class="flex-grow max-w-7xl w-full mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-6 sm:py-10">

    <!-- Title Section -->
    <div class="mb-8 text-center sm:text-left">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight font-sans">
        Roth Conversion Calculator
      </h1>
      <div class="mt-4 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3 text-xs font-medium text-slate-500 bg-slate-900/50 inline-flex px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg border border-slate-800">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-1.5">
          <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-4 w-4 text-[#00F5D4]" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m5.618-4.016A11.955 11.955 0 0112 2.944a11.955 11.955 0 01-8.618 3.04A12.02 12.02 0 003 9c0 5.591 3.824 10.29 9 11.622 5.176-1.332 9-6.03 9-11.622 0-1.042-.133-2.052-.382-3.016z"/></svg>
          <span>Reviewed by <a href="/editorial-policy/" class="text-slate-400 hover:text-[#00F5D4] transition-colors underline decoration-slate-700 underline-offset-2">Editorial Staff</a></span>
        </div>
        <span class="hidden sm:inline text-slate-700">&bull;</span>
        <time datetime="2026-07-21" class="text-slate-400">Updated: July 2026</time>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 mt-2 max-w-2xl leading-relaxed">
        Model the tax cost of converting a traditional IRA or 401(k) to a Roth IRA today, and find the breakeven future tax rate where conversion actually pays off.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Calculator Component Island -->
    <RothConversionCalculator />

    <!-- Explainer Content -->
    <div class="border-t border-slate-800/60 mt-12 bg-gradient-to-b from-slate-950 to-slate-950/95">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto py-16">
        <section>
          <div class="mb-6">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-indigo-500/10 text-indigo-400 border border-indigo-500/20 mb-4">Financial Tool</span>
            <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight leading-snug">
              Find Your Personal Roth Conversion Breakeven
            </h2>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-8 text-sm text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            <article>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-3">Introduction</h3>
              <p>Converting a traditional IRA or 401(k) to a Roth IRA means paying income tax on the converted amount today, in exchange for tax-free growth and tax-free withdrawals later. Whether that trade is worth it depends entirely on how your current tax rate compares to your future one — which is exactly why this calculator shows a breakeven rate instead of a single yes-or-no answer.</p>
            </article>

            <article>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-3">Key Benefits</h3>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
                <li>See your exact conversion tax bill before you commit.</li>
                <li>Compare ending balances under both paths side by side.</li>
                <li>Find your personal breakeven future tax rate.</li>
                <li>Understand the cost of paying conversion tax from the IRA itself vs. from savings.</li>
              </ul>
            </article>
          </div>

          <!-- FAQ Accordion -->
          <div class="mt-12 border-t border-slate-800/80 pt-10">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-amber-500/10 text-amber-400 border border-amber-500/20 mb-4">FAQ</span>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h3>

            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/50">
                <button class="w-full flex items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-left group cursor-pointer" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle('hidden'); this.querySelector('svg').classList.toggle('rotate-180');">
                  <span class="font-semibold text-white">Why would I pay taxes now instead of later?</span>
                  <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
                </button>
                <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6 text-sm text-slate-400">
                  Converting makes the most sense when your current marginal tax rate is lower than the rate you expect to pay in retirement — for example, in a low-income year, after a business loss, or before required minimum distributions push you into a higher bracket later.
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/50">
                <button class="w-full flex items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-left group cursor-pointer" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle('hidden'); this.querySelector('svg').classList.toggle('rotate-180');">
                  <span class="font-semibold text-white">What's the difference between paying conversion tax from the IRA vs. from savings?</span>
                  <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
                </button>
                <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6 text-sm text-slate-400">
                  Paying the conversion tax from outside savings lets the full converted amount grow tax-free in the Roth. Paying it from the IRA itself reduces the amount that converts and grows tax-free, and for those under 59½ it may also count as an early withdrawal subject to a 10% penalty on that portion.
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/50">
                <button class="w-full flex items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-left group cursor-pointer" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle('hidden'); this.querySelector('svg').classList.toggle('rotate-180');">
                  <span class="font-semibold text-white">Can I convert only part of my traditional IRA?</span>
                  <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
                </button>
                <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6 text-sm text-slate-400">
                  Yes. Many people convert smaller amounts over several years — sometimes called a conversion ladder — to stay within a target tax bracket each year rather than converting a large balance all at once.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Internal Links -->
          <div class="mt-12 border-t border-slate-800/80 pt-10">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Related Calculators &amp; Resources</h3>
            <div class="flex flex-col space-y-2">
              <a href="/buy-borrow-die-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">Buy, Borrow, Die Calculator</a>
              <a href="/s-corp-tax-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">S-Corp Tax Calculator</a>
              <a href="/qbi-deduction-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">QBI Deduction Calculator</a>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Methodology & Sources -->
          <div class="mt-12 border-t border-slate-800/80 pt-10">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-emerald-500/10 text-emerald-400 border border-emerald-500/20 mb-4">Methodology</span>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">How This is Calculated</h3>
            <div class="text-sm text-slate-400 space-y-3 leading-relaxed">
              <p>This calculator compares two paths for the same dollar amount over your chosen time horizon. Staying traditional grows the balance tax-deferred at your assumed return, then applies your expected future marginal rate at withdrawal. Converting to Roth pays your current marginal rate on the conversion now, then grows the remaining principal tax-free — either the full converted amount (if you pay the tax from outside funds) or the converted amount minus the tax owed (if you pay it from the IRA itself). The breakeven rate shown is the future tax rate at which both paths produce the same ending value.</p>
              <p>This is a simplified, deterministic model — it assumes a constant annual return and doesn't account for early-withdrawal penalties, Medicare IRMAA surcharges, or state tax differences. Consult a tax professional for your specific situation.</p>
              <p><strong>Official Source:</strong> <a href="https://www.irs.gov/retirement-plans/roth-iras" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-emerald-400 hover:underline">IRS.gov — Roth IRAs</a></p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>
